@ChroniclesOfAzu @br00bs thank you 💗 for real, broobs' art is so dope and an important continuation of this history!

These artists, whether they were printing in the 70's or are circulating their images on ig now, created a visual language for the truth that really underscores all liberation movements, imo. 

That like @br00bs said, “Black liberation means liberation for literally everybody."

And of course, about the women who were instrumental in  the largely-boys club that was Chicano art movement. 

Though not purely a printmaker, Ester Hernandez' 1982 'Sun Mad' print is one of the most recognizable images in the Chicano Art movement.

This only scratches the surface of the significance of political posters within the Chicano art movement and beyond. So much be said abt the influence of global collective OSPAAL, abt the way Dignidad Rebelde not only make art but preserve history by printing archival work.

And here are some of my favorite posters of Juan R. Fuentes: calling for the liberation of Palestine in 1977, announcing a benefit for El Tecolote (longest-running bilingual paper in the US!) and for the World Women's Conference in Kenya in 1985. https://t.co/RgkkDAdaJS

But everything's come full circle, or rather has never gone away. Here are two posters Malaquias Montoya did in the 70's about police brutality in San Leandro, spurred by the killing of 27-year-old Jose Barlow Benavidez in 1976. https://t.co/tOa0JXU1wh

“Art … should be something that identifies what it is that keeps us oppressed and somehow gives us a light on how we free ourselves from that oppression,” — Malaquias Montoya. 

Their art was a kind of public political education that met community members where they were.

Political posters are the root of Chicano art, especially in the Bay. 

A pleasure to talk to @br00bs, Jesus Barraza and Chicano art ogs Juan R. Fuentes & Malaquias Montoya about solidarity with global liberation movements thru public art.

https://t.co/zDa5m45HPa
